Balancing class¶

Increaseing the class 1 with 50% of size with respect class 0 using SMOTE Technique and reducing the class 0 to 80% with respect to class 1 randomly

In [6]:
# Here data is imbalance which lead to the baised model creation
# Split features and target
X = df.drop('Diabetes_binary', axis=1)
y = df['Diabetes_binary']

# Define SMOTE and UnderSampler
smote = SMOTE(sampling_strategy=0.5, random_state=42)  # Make class 1 50% the size of class 0
under = RandomUnderSampler(sampling_strategy=0.8, random_state=42)  # Reduce class 0 to 80% of class 1

# Combine in a pipeline
pipeline = Pipeline(steps=[('smote', smote), ('under', under)])

# Apply the pipeline
X_resampled, y_resampled = pipeline.fit_resample(X, y)

# Define the pipeline
pipeline = make_pipeline(
    StandardScaler(),
    LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000)
)

# Define hyperparameter grid (match solver with penalty compatibility)
param_grid = [
    {
        'logisticregression__penalty': ['l2'],
        'logisticregression__C': [0.01, 0.1, 1],
        'logisticregression__solver': ['lbfgs', 'liblinear']
    },
    {
        'logisticregression__penalty': ['l1'],
        'logisticregression__C': [0.01, 0.1, 1],
        'logisticregression__solver': ['lbfgs','liblinear']
    }
]

# Apply GridSearchCV
grid_search = GridSearchCV(
    estimator=pipeline,
    param_grid=param_grid,
    cv=5,
    scoring='accuracy',
    n_jobs=-1,
    verbose=1
)

# Fit GridSearch on the resampled data
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Best model
model_lr = grid_search.best_estimator_

# Predictions
y_pred_log = model_lr.predict(X_test)
y_prob_log = model_lr.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

# Confusion Matrix
cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_log)
ConfusionMatrixDisplay(cm, display_labels=["No Diabetes", "Diabetes"]).plot(cmap="Blues")
plt.title("Confusion Matrix - Best Logistic Regression")
plt.show()

# Classification Report
print("Best Parameters - Logistic Regression:", model_lr)
print("Classification Report - Best Logistic Regression")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_log, target_names=["No Diabetes", "Diabetes"]))

SVM¶

Why SVM Might Not Be Efficient with 21 Features:¶

  1. Not Ideal for Large Datasets

    • SVMs can be computationally expensive, especially when the dataset has tens of thousands of rows (as in your case).
    • Training time increases rapidly with more data points and more features.

  2. Harder to Tune with Many Features

    • SVMs require choosing the right kernel (linear, rbf, poly, etc.), along with hyperparameters like C and gamma.
    • With 21 features, the search space becomes large and hyperparameter tuning becomes complex and slow.

  3. Feature Scaling is Critical

    • SVMs are very sensitive to feature scales, meaning you need perfect standardization of all 21 features.
    • Even small inconsistencies can reduce performance.

  4. Less Interpretability

    • In logistic regression or decision trees, it's easier to interpret which features are important.
    • SVMs (especially with non-linear kernels) act like a black box, which makes feature influence analysis difficult.

  5. Memory Inefficient

    • For large datasets, SVMs often require more memory due to the support vectors it must store and work with during inference.

  6. Other Models Perform Competitively

    • Your results already show that Logistic Regression, Random Forest, and Gradient Boosting perform equally well or better with:
      • Better training speed
      • Easier tuning
      • Higher interpretability

In summary, for your dataset with 21 features and many samples, SVMs are less efficient both in terms of computation and model manageability. You're better off with tree-based models or regularized logistic regression, as your evaluation already shows.

Conclusion:¶

  • Best Performing Model: XGBoost, followed by Random Forest
  • Most Interpretable: Logistic Regression, Decision Tree
  • Best for Simplicity & Speed: Naive Bayes
  • Best for Lazy Learning: KNN, though less scalable
